[src:express-middleware/express-js] The original author, TJ Holowaychuk, described it as a Sinatra-inspired server, meaning that it is relatively minimal with many features available as plugins.
[src:express-middleware/express-js] Express is the back-end component of popular development stacks like the MEAN, MERN or MEVN stack, together with the MongoDB database software and a JavaScript front-end framework or library.
[src:express-middleware/express-js] Express.js was founded by TJ Holowaychuk.
[src:express-middleware/express-js] The initial versions were created in early 2010, and milestone version 1 was released later that year.
[src:express-middleware/express-js] In June 2014, rights to manage the project were acquired by StrongLoop.
[src:express-middleware/express-js] StrongLoop was acquired by IBM in September 2015; in January 2016, IBM announced that it would place Express.js under the stewardship of the Node.js Foundation incubator.
[src:express-middleware/express-js] In July 2014, work began towards milestone version 5.
[src:express-middleware/express-js] After ten years of development it was released in October 2024.
[src:express-middleware/express-js] Express.js is used by Fox Sports, PayPal, Uber and IBM.
[src:express-middleware/express-js] The following program will respond to HTTP GET requests with the text "Hi, your request has been received", and listen to the port the program is running on (in this case, port 2000).
[src:express-middleware/expressjs-express] This is a Node.js module available through the npm registry.
[src:express-middleware/expressjs-express] Before installing, download and install Node.js.
[src:express-middleware/expressjs-express] If this is a brand new project, make sure to create a `package.json` first with the `npm init` command.
[src:express-middleware/expressjs-express] Follow our installing guide for more information.
[src:express-middleware/expressjs-express] The Express philosophy is to provide small, robust tooling for HTTP servers, making it a great solution for single page applications, websites, hybrids, or public HTTP APIs.
[src:express-middleware/expressjs-express] Express does not force you to use any specific ORM or template engine.
[src:express-middleware/expressjs-express] With support for over 14 template engines via @ladjs/consolidate, you can quickly craft your perfect framework.
[src:express-middleware/expressjs-express] The Express.js project welcomes all constructive contributions.
[src:express-middleware/expressjs-express] Contributions take many forms, from code for bug fixes and enhancements, to additions and fixes to documentation, additional tests, triaging incoming pull requests and issues, and more!
[src:express-middleware/expressjs-express] See the Contributing Guide for more technical details on contributing.
[src:express-middleware/expressjs-express] If you discover a security vulnerability in Express, please see Security Policies and Procedures.
[src:express-middleware/expressjs-express] For information about the governance of the express.js project, see GOVERNANCE.md.
[src:express-middleware/http-methods] HTTP defines a set of **request methods** to indicate the purpose of the request and what is expected if the request is successful.
[src:express-middleware/http-methods] Although they can also be nouns, these request methods are sometimes referred to as *HTTP verbs*.
[src:express-middleware/http-methods] Each request method has its own semantics, but some characteristics are shared across multiple methods, specifically request methods can be safe, idempotent, or cacheable.
[src:express-middleware/http-methods] The `GET` method requests a representation of the specified resource.
[src:express-middleware/http-methods] Requests using `GET` should only retrieve data and should not contain a request content.
[src:express-middleware/http-methods] The `HEAD` method asks for a response identical to a `GET` request, but without a response body.
[src:express-middleware/http-methods] The `POST` method submits an entity to the specified resource, often causing a change in state or side effects on the server.
[src:express-middleware/http-methods] The `PUT` method replaces all current representations of the target resource with the request content.
[src:express-middleware/http-methods] The `DELETE` method deletes the specified resource.
[src:express-middleware/http-methods] The `CONNECT` method establishes a tunnel to the server identified by the target resource.
[src:express-middleware/http-methods] The `OPTIONS` method describes the communication options for the target resource.
[src:express-middleware/http-methods] The `TRACE` method performs a message loop-back test along the path to the target resource.
[src:express-middleware/http-methods] The `PATCH` method applies partial modifications to a resource.
[src:express-middleware/http-methods] The following table lists HTTP request methods and their categorization in terms of safety, cacheability, and idempotency.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] HTTP response status codes indicate whether a specific HTTP request has been successfully completed.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The status codes listed below are defined by RFC 9110.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This interim response indicates that the client should continue the request or ignore the response if the request is already finished.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This code is sent in response to an `Upgrade` request header from the client and indicates the protocol the server is switching to.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This code was used in WebDAV contexts to indicate that a request has been received by the server, but no status was available at the time of the response.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This status code is primarily intended to be used with the `Link` header, letting the user agent start preloading resources while the server prepares a response or preconnect to an origin from which the page will need resources.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The request succeeded, and a new resource was created as a result.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This is typically the response sent after `POST` requests, or some `PUT` requests.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The request has been received but not yet acted upon.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] It is noncommittal, since there is no way in HTTP to later send an asynchronous response indicating the outcome of the request.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] It is intended for cases where another process or server handles the request, or for batch processing.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This response code means the returned metadata is not exactly the same as is available from the origin server, but is collected from a local or a third-party copy.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This is mostly used for mirrors or backups of another resource.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] Except for that specific case, the `200 OK` response is preferred to this status.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] There is no content to send for this request, but the headers are useful.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The user agent may update its cached headers for this resource with the new ones.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] Tells the user agent to reset the document which sent this request.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This response code is used in response to a range request when the client has requested a part or parts of a resource.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] Conveys information about multiple resources, for situations where multiple status codes might be appropriate.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] Used inside a `<dav:propstat>` response element to avoid repeatedly enumerating the internal members of multiple bindings to the same collection.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The server has fulfilled a `GET` request for the resource, and the response is a representation of the result of one or more instance-manipulations applied to the current instance.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] In agent-driven content negotiation, the request has more than one possible response and the user agent or user should choose one of them.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] There is no standardized way for clients to automatically choose one of the responses, so this is rarely used.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The URL of the requested resource has been changed permanently.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This response code means that the URI of requested resource has been changed *temporarily*.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] Further changes in the URI might be made in the future, so the same URI should be used by the client in future requests.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The server sent this response to direct the client to get the requested resource at another URI with a `GET` request.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] It tells the client that the response has not been modified, so the client can continue to use the same cached version of the response.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] Defined in a previous version of the HTTP specification to indicate that a requested response must be accessed by a proxy.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] It has been deprecated due to security concerns regarding in-band configuration of a proxy.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This response code is no longer used; but is reserved.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] It was used in a previous version of the HTTP/1.1 specification.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The server sends this response to direct the client to get the requested resource at another URI with the same method that was used in the prior request.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This has the same semantics as the `302 Found` response code, with the exception that the user agent *must not* change the HTTP method used: if a `POST` was used in the first request, a `POST` must be used in the redirected request.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This means that the resource is now permanently located at another URI, specified by the `Location` response header.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This has the same semantics as the `301 Moved Permanently` HTTP response code, with the exception that the user agent *must not* change the HTTP method used: if a `POST` was used in the first request, a `POST` must be used in the second request.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The server cannot or will not process the request due to something that is perceived to be a client error (e.g., malformed request syntax, invalid request message framing, or deceptive request routing).
[src:express-middleware/http-status] Although the HTTP standard specifies "unauthorized", semantically this response means "unauthenticated".
[src:express-middleware/http-status] That is, the client must authenticate itself to get the requested response.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The initial purpose of this code was for digital payment systems, however this status code is rarely used and no standard convention exists.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The client does not have access rights to the content; that is, it is unauthorized, so the server is refusing to give the requested resource.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] Unlike `401 Unauthorized`, the client's identity is known to the server.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The server cannot find the requested resource.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] In the browser, this means the URL is not recognized.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] In an API, this can also mean that the endpoint is valid but the resource itself does not exist.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] Servers may also send this response instead of `403 Forbidden` to hide the existence of a resource from an unauthorized client.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This response code is probably the most well known due to its frequent occurrence on the web.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The request method is known by the server but is not supported by the target resource.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] For example, an API may not allow `DELETE` on a resource, or the `TRACE` method entirely.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This response is sent when the web server, after performing server-driven content negotiation, doesn't find any content that conforms to the criteria given by the user agent.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This is similar to `401 Unauthorized` but authentication is needed to be done by a proxy.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This response is sent on an idle connection by some servers, even without any previous request by the client.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] It means that the server would like to shut down this unused connection.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This response is used much more since some browsers use HTTP pre-connection mechanisms to speed up browsing.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] Some servers may shut down a connection without sending this message.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This response is sent when a request conflicts with the current state of the server.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] In WebDAV remote web authoring, `409` responses are errors sent to the client so that a user might be able to resolve a conflict and resubmit the request.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This response is sent when the requested content has been permanently deleted from server, with no forwarding address.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] Clients are expected to remove their caches and links to the resource.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The HTTP specification intends this status code to be used for "limited-time, promotional services".
[src:express-middleware/http-status] APIs should not feel compelled to indicate resources that have been deleted with this status code.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] Server rejected the request because the `Content-Length` header field is not defined and the server requires it.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] In conditional requests, the client has indicated preconditions in its headers which the server does not meet.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The request body is larger than limits defined by server.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The server might close the connection or return a `Retry-After` header field.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The URI requested by the client is longer than the server is willing to interpret.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The media format of the requested data is not supported by the server, so the server is rejecting the request.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The ranges specified by the `Range` header field in the request cannot be fulfilled.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] It's possible that the range is outside the size of the target resource's data.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This response code means the expectation indicated by the `Expect` request header field cannot be met by the server.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The server refuses the attempt to brew coffee with a teapot.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The request was directed at a server that is not able to produce a response.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This can be sent by a server that is not configured to produce responses for the combination of scheme and authority that are included in the request URI.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The request was well-formed but was unable to be followed due to semantic errors.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The resource that is being accessed is locked.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The request failed due to failure of a previous request.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] Indicates that the server is unwilling to risk processing a request that might be replayed.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The server refuses to perform the request using the current protocol but might be willing to do so after the client upgrades to a different protocol.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The server sends an `Upgrade` header in a 426 response to indicate the required protocol(s).
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The origin server requires the request to be conditional.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This response is intended to prevent the 'lost update' problem, where a client `GET`s a resource's state, modifies it and `PUT`s it back to the server, when meanwhile a third party has modified the state on the server, leading to a conflict.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The user has sent too many requests in a given amount of time (rate limiting).
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The server is unwilling to process the request because its header fields are too large.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The request may be resubmitted after reducing the size of the request header fields.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The user agent requested a resource that cannot legally be provided, such as a web page censored by a government.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The server has encountered a situation it does not know how to handle.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This error is generic, indicating that the server cannot find a more appropriate `5XX` status code to respond with.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The request method is not supported by the server and cannot be handled.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The only methods that servers are required to support (and therefore must not return this code) are `GET` and `HEAD`.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This error response means that the server, while working as a gateway to get a response needed to handle the request, got an invalid response.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The server is not ready to handle the request.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] Common causes are a server that is down for maintenance or that is overloaded.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] Note that together with this response, a user-friendly page explaining the problem should be sent.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This response should be used for temporary conditions and the `Retry-After` HTTP header should, if possible, contain the estimated time before the recovery of the service.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The webmaster must also take care about the caching-related headers that are sent along with this response, as these temporary condition responses should usually not be cached.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] This error response is given when the server is acting as a gateway and cannot get a response in time.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The HTTP version used in the request is not supported by the server.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The server has an internal configuration error: during content negotiation, the chosen variant is configured to engage in content negotiation itself, which results in circular references when creating responses.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The method could not be performed on the resource because the server is unable to store the representation needed to successfully complete the request.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The server detected an infinite loop while processing the request.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] The client request declares an HTTP Extension (RFC 2774) that should be used to process the request, but the extension is not supported.
[src:express-middleware/http-status] Indicates that the client needs to authenticate to gain network access.
[src:express-middleware/middleware] Middleware makes it easier for software developers to implement communication and input/output, so they can focus on the specific purpose of their application.
[src:express-middleware/middleware] It gained popularity in the 1980s as a solution to the problem of how to link newer applications to older legacy systems, although the term had been in use since 1968.
[src:express-middleware/middleware] The term is most commonly used for software that enables communication and management of data in distributed applications.
[src:express-middleware/middleware] An IETF workshop in 2000 defined middleware as "those services found above the transport (i.e. over TCP/IP) layer set of services but below the application environment" (i.e. below application-level APIs).
[src:express-middleware/middleware] In this more specific sense *middleware* can be described as the hyphen ("-") in *client-server*, or the *-to-* in *peer-to-peer*.
[src:express-middleware/middleware] Middleware includes web servers, application servers, content management systems, and similar tools that support application development and delivery.
[src:express-middleware/middleware] Database access services are often characterised as middleware.
[src:express-middleware/middleware] Some of them are language specific implementations and support heterogeneous features and other related communication features.
[src:express-middleware/middleware] Examples of database-oriented middleware include ODBC, JDBC, and transaction processing monitors.
[src:express-middleware/middleware] Distributed computing system middleware can loosely be divided into two categories—those that provide human-time services (such as web request servicing) and those that perform in machine-time.
[src:express-middleware/middleware] This latter middleware is somewhat standardized through the Service Availability Forum and is commonly used in complex, embedded systems within the telecom, defence, and aerospace industries.
[src:express-middleware/middleware] Many categories of middleware have been defined, based on the field in which it is used or the application module it serves.
[src:express-middleware/middleware] The term *middleware* is used in other contexts as well.
[src:express-middleware/middleware] *Middleware* is sometimes used in a similar sense to a software driver, an abstraction layer that hides detail about hardware devices or other software from an application.
[src:express-middleware/representational-state-transfer] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:express-middleware/representational-state-transfer] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:express-middleware/representational-state-transfer] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:express-middleware/representational-state-transfer] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:express-middleware/representational-state-transfer] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:express-middleware/representational-state-transfer] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:express-middleware/representational-state-transfer] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:express-middleware/representational-state-transfer] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:express-middleware/representational-state-transfer] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:express-middleware/representational-state-transfer] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:express-middleware/representational-state-transfer] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:express-middleware/representational-state-transfer] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:express-middleware/representational-state-transfer] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:express-middleware/representational-state-transfer] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:express-middleware/representational-state-transfer] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:express-middleware/representational-state-transfer] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:express-middleware/representational-state-transfer] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:express-middleware/representational-state-transfer] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:express-middleware/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:express-middleware/representational-state-transfer] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:express-middleware/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:express-middleware/representational-state-transfer] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:express-middleware/representational-state-transfer] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:express-middleware/representational-state-transfer] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] Express is a routing and middleware web framework that has minimal functionality of its own: An Express application is essentially a series of middleware function calls.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] If the current middleware function does not end the request-response cycle, it must call `next()` to pass control to the next middleware function.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] Otherwise, the request will be left hanging.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] You can load application-level and router-level middleware with an optional mount path.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] You can also load a series of middleware functions together, which creates a sub-stack of the middleware system at a mount point.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] Bind application-level middleware to an instance of the app object by using the `app.use()` and `app.METHOD()` functions, where `METHOD` is the HTTP method of the request that the middleware function handles (such as GET, PUT, or POST) in lowercase.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] This example shows a middleware function with no mount path.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] The function is executed every time the app receives a request.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] This example shows a middleware function mounted on the `/user/:id` path.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] The function is executed for any type of HTTP request on the `/user/:id` path.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] This example shows a route and its handler function (middleware system).
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] The function handles GET requests to the `/user/:id` path.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] Here is an example of loading a series of middleware functions at a mount point, with a mount path.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] It illustrates a middleware sub-stack that prints request info for any type of HTTP request to the `/user/:id` path.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] Route handlers enable you to define multiple routes for a path.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] The example below defines two routes for GET requests to the `/user/:id` path.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] The second route will not cause any problems, but it will never get called because the first route ends the request-response cycle.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] This example shows a middleware sub-stack that handles GET requests to the `/user/:id` path.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] To skip the rest of the middleware functions from a router middleware stack, call `next('route')` to pass control to the next route.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] `next('route')` will work only in middleware functions that were loaded by using the `app.METHOD()` or `router.METHOD()` functions.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] Middleware can also be declared in an array for reusability.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] Router-level middleware works in the same way as application-level middleware, except it is bound to an instance of `express.Router()`.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] Load router-level middleware by using the `router.use()` and `router.METHOD()` functions.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] To skip the rest of the router’s middleware functions, call `next('router')` to pass control back out of the router instance.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] Error-handling middleware always takes *four* arguments.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] You must provide four arguments to identify it as an error-handling middleware function.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] Even if you don’t need to use the `next` object, you must specify it to maintain the signature.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] Otherwise, the `next` object will be interpreted as regular middleware and will fail to handle errors.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] For details about error-handling middleware, see: Error handling.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] Starting with version 4.x, Express no longer depends on Connect.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] The middleware functions that were previously included with Express are now in separate modules; see the list of middleware functions.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] Use third-party middleware to add functionality to Express apps.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] Install the Node.js module for the required functionality, then load it in your app at the application level or at the router level.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] The following example illustrates installing and loading the cookie-parsing middleware function `cookie-parser`.
[src:express-middleware/using-middleware] For a partial list of third-party middleware functions that are commonly used with Express, see: Third-party middleware.
